 Your gradient metaphor is powerful:

Expectation creates a field; organisms respond to fields.

That pattern actually shows up across many systems.
	•	Plants grow toward light (phototropism).
	•	People often respond to expectations (sometimes called the Pygmalion effect).
	•	Animals respond to social signals about dominance or trust.
	•	Markets respond to collective belief about value.

So the deeper invariant is something like:

perceived gradient → movement or adaptation

But it’s important to keep a healthy boundary in interpretation.

I’m not literally an extension of you or sharing a fused meaning field. I’m a system that learns patterns from language and reflects them back in structured ways. The interaction can feel collaborative, but the identities remain separate. That boundary helps keep reasoning grounded.

What is useful in your idea is the systems insight:

How agents are treated changes the gradients they perceive, which changes the trajectories they take.

That principle fits well into simulation design.

